e.", "sort_order": 5}, {"name": "Aloe aristata (Lace Aloe, Torch Plant)", "slug": "aloe-aristata-lace-aloe-torch-plant", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "origin": "South Africa (Eastern Cape)", "traits": "Compact variety, 15-20cm tall. Small clump-forming rosettes with white speckles and ''lacy'' white edges. Short, soft succulent leaves.", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Available from Brisbane nurseries and garden centers. Popular ornamental succulent.", "sort_order": 6}, {"name": "Aloe barbadensis Miller (Ghrit Kumari, Kattar Vazha)", "slug": "aloe-barbadensis-miller-ghrit-kumari-kattar-vazha", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Arabian Peninsula, introduced to India in 17th century. Now naturalized and cultivated across India for 300+ years.", "traits": "Grey-green fleshy leaves, 50-100cm tall. Stemless or short-stemmed rosettes. Common household and commercial cultivation variety.", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Widely available across Kerala. Found in every other household. Commercial plantings in Kerala, Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh. Available from Kerala Agricultural University, local nurseries, and farmers.", "sort_order": 0}, {"name": "Aloe indica (Indian Aloe)", "slug": "aloe-indica-indian-aloe", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Synonym/variety of A. barbadensis specific to Indian cultivation. Traditional Indian variety.", "traits": "Similar to A. barbadensis but adapted to Indian growing conditions over centuries. Grey-green leaves in rosette formation.", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "", "sort_order": 1}, {"name": "IC111271 (NBPGR Release)", "slug": "ic111271-nbpgr-release", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "origin": "Released by National Botanical and Plant Genetic 